We recommended that Management:
Issue a memorandum for all collectors/AOs to enforce daily/prompt and intact remittance of all collections, and to impose sanctions against erring collectors/AOs pursuant to pertinent laws, rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to closely and regularly monitor the remittances by collectors/tellers;
Review its internal control processes on the manner of collections and subsequent remittance and institute measures to curtail the delay in the deposits of these collections;
Designate an alternate officer to take over the duties and responsibilities of the Municipal Treasurer in the latter’s absence or when on official travel; and
Assess the manpower / workforce vis-à-vis the delegation of duties/tasks in the MTO, and consider any adjustments or reinforcements thereto, if necessary.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Ensure correct and prompt remittance of taxes withheld to avoid unnecessary penalties;
Set a cut-off for the submission of Abstract of Collections and RCDs by the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to the Municipal Accounting Office;
Consider filing an amended return with the BIR to correct, add, or omit details from a previously declared return, such as the proper recognition of tax due (DST, EWT, VAT withheld, and OPT withheld) for a specific period, ensuring accuracy and compliance, provided no BIR Letter of Authority has been issued for CY 2024; and
Institute measures to improve the withholding and remittance of taxes to ensure that the unremitted taxes at year-end only include those withheld during the last month of the year.

We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant to assess/evaluate the condition of all dormant receivables in order to determine whether which are still recoverable and/or which are subject to possible write-off.

For receivables determined to be recoverable, exhaust all possible remedies to enforce collection thereof.  Likewise, issue demand letters to the identified individuals/employees and NGAs to immediately liquidate their cash advances; 

For receivables determined to be beyond recovery in consonance with COA Circular No. 2016-005, facilitate the filing of request for authority to write-off following the guidelines and procedures set forth in the Circular.  Also, recognize impairment for accounts no longer collectible pursuant to the aforementioned accounting standards.

We recommended to the Mayor:
To fully adhere to Section 266 of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs Volume I by conducting annual physical count of PPE;
To designate Property Officer responsible for monitoring, maintaining and updating of Property Cards;
To designate a Committee to spearhead yearly conduct of Physical Inventory Count of all the properties of the Municipality;

Through the designated Property Officer and Physical Inventory team to

Prepare, inspect, evaluate and assess fully depreciated and unserviceable properties that will be subject for disposal;
Prepare program for disposal with time schedules in accordance with COA Circular NO. 89-296 January 27,1989;
Submit Inventory Report showing the itemized list and complete description of the assets such as the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) and;
Submit Appraisal Report showing the appraised values of the assets, prepared by an in-house and/or independent appraiser and the Disposal procedure adopted.

Thru the Accounting Unit to:
Assist the Property Officer in the establishment of correct and actual amounts of inventories, properties and equipment for disposal;
Assist the Physical Inventory team in the Submission of reports required for the Disposal of items in accordance with COA Circular No. 89-296 dated January 27,1989. 
Record appropriate accounting entries upon disposal and submit journal entry vouchers and supporting documents thereof.

We recommended that Management:
In coordination with the Human Resource/Personnel Unit, evaluate / assess the need to establish a General Service Office (GSO) which shall be responsible, among others, in the management of supplies, properties, buildings, and other facilities;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all PPEs and furnish complete reports using the prescribed format of the RPCPPE;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian to prepare / maintain the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, and thereafter ensure regular reconciliation thereof and other related records;
Require the Municipal Accountant to update the Subsidiary Ledgers for each class of PPE account to provide reliable details or breakdown of and to properly support the balances appearing in the General Ledger;
Direct the Inventory Committee, Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to conduct reconciliation of data in the RPCPPE with the accounting and property records; and
Consider conducting the one-time cleansing of PPE in which upon completion of the proper conduct of physical count:
Instruct the Property Custodian to determine the person/s accountable for any non-existing/missing PPEs based on the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs), PCs and other available property records, and thereafter issue demand letters to produce the missing PPE; and
Direct the Inventory Team, the Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to refer to Sections 7 to 9 of the same COA Circular for the procedures in the disposition and derecognition of any non-existing/missing PPEs.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to record purchases of supplies/materials for stock under the appropriate Inventory Account;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the concerned custodian of the inventories to prepare the SLCs (Annex J) for each commodity/stock and Stock Cards (Annex K), respectively, and thereafter ensure regular reconciliation thereof and other related records;
Strictly require the weekly preparation of SSMI (Annex L) to support the recognition of supplies/materials issuances as expenses pursuant to Section 121 of NGAS Manual Vol. 1;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct semestral physical count of inventory items by type and submit the required Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) (Annex M) to the auditor; and
For the Drugs and Medicines and Accountable Forms Inventory, instruct the Municipal Health Officer and the Municipal Treasurer to maintain Stock Cards and SSMI, respectively, to properly account the receipts and issuances of the inventories.

We recommended that Management:

Formulate strategies in order to complete the physical count of PPEs by ensuring that it is given priority and conducted as scheduled;

In the preparation of the inventory report, use the RPCPPE form and fill in all the data required therein, furnishing the Auditor a copy thereof;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Acting Property Custodian to prepare the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, and thereafter ensure regular reconciliation thereof and other related records.  Also, conduct reconciliation of data in the PPELCs, PCs and other property records to address the above variances/differences between the PPE costs per inventory report and accounting record; 

   Upon completion of the physical count:

Instruct the Acting Property Custodian to determine the person/s accountable for any non-existing/missing PPEs based on the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs), PCs and other available property records, and thereafter issue demand letters to produce the missing PPE; and

Direct the Inventory Team, the Acting Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to refer to Sections 7 to 9 of the same COA circular for the procedures in the disposition and derecognition of any non-existing/missing PPEs.

We recommended to the Management to:

	Specify in the Notes to Financial Statements the Breakdown of the ₱2,599,330 Breeding Stocks;
	Require the conduct of Physical Inventory of the Breeding Stocks/animals and recommend the participation/inclusion of the Municipal Agricultural Officer as a member of the Inventory Team;
	Investigate the status of the Breeding stocks amounting to ₱966,830.00 ageing for more than 12 years with efforts to provide supporting documents;
	Explain the difference from the granted ₱1,970,000 from the booked ₱1,632,500.00 of Breeding Stocks;
	Submit proof of submission of request for relief of accountability of the aforementioned dead breeding stock, along with the Biological Assets that were exchanged in payment of the dead cattle/carabao;
	Require the General Services Officer/ Municipal Treasurer to Maintain Property Cards for the Breeding Stocks and;
	Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain the Work, Other Animals, and Breeding Stocks Ledger Card (WOABSLC) as provided under Section 114 of NGAS Manual.

We recommended to the Management to:

•	Submit explanation why all employees were granted Personnel Motivation Incentive (Monetary Award) despite absence of PRAISE Committee evaluation as to individual suggestions, inventions, superior accomplishments and other personal efforts and how these efforts resulted to monetary savings of the LGU and why these transactions should not be disallowed in audit;

•	Discontinue payment of monetary awards in the absence of such PRAISE Committee evaluation;

